# DORA Core Model

Measures how fast and safely a team delivers. Bridge between product strategy and technical execution.

## 4 Metrics
- **Deployment Frequency (DF):** How often code deploys to prod
- **Lead Time (LT):** Commit → running in prod
- **Change Failure Rate (CFR):** % deploys causing incident
- **MTTR:** Time to restore from failure

## Performance Tiers
| Tier | DF | LT | CFR | MTTR |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Elite | on-demand | <1h | 0–5% | <1h |
| High | daily–weekly | 1d–1wk | 6–15% | <1d |
| Medium | weekly–monthly | 1wk–1mo | 16–30% | 1d–1wk |
| Low | monthly–6mo | 1mo–6mo | 16–30% | >1wk |

## Top Capabilities (highest impact)
- Loosely coupled architecture → DF (#1 predictor)
- Trunk-based dev + CI → LT ↓
- Test automation + DRE → CFR ↓
- Observability + blameless culture → MTTR ↓
- Small batches + no manual approval gates → LT ↓

## Integration
- `diffusion-release-tracking`: DF is prerequisite for Rogers gate iteration speed. Low DF → fix before phased rollout
- `collaborative-engineering-agent`: Atomic PRs → LT ↓, DRE → CFR ↓, fix-branch → MTTR ↓
- `c4-model` + `ddd-core`: Loosely coupled arch via independent containers (C4 L2) + Bounded Contexts (DDD)
- `business-product-leadership`: Elite DF enables rapid MVP validation; Low DF = delivery is the bottleneck

## Anti-Patterns
- High DF + high CFR = fast failure, not fast delivery
- Manual approval gates: biggest LT killer, no CFR benefit
- MTTR reduced by observability + safety, not more process
- DORA as performance review → diagnostic tool only
